b'#BarodaStartupBanking was inaugurated by Finance Secretary Shri Rajiv Kumar along with #BankofBaroda MD & CEO Shri Sanjiv Chadha, EDs Shri Murali Ramaswami, Shri S L Jain & Shri Vikramaditya Singh Khichi. This initiative is aimed at making the Bank a preferred banking partner for the start-up community & establishing connect with at least 2,000 start-ups over the next 2 years. It was launched simultaneously across 15 cities in the country.\n\nThese Baroda Startup branches will offer a bouquet of tailor-made banking products and services that have been designed keeping in mind the unique and specialized banking requirements of start-ups and also provide dedicated Relationship Managers. The products include customised current accounts, state-of-the-art payments gateways, corporate credit cards, corporate salary accounts and credit facilities apart from other existing products of the bank. In addition to end-to-end banking solutions for start-ups, it aims to meet ancillary needs of start-ups by partnering with marquee service providers to assist start-ups by way of cloud credits, mentorship, co-working space, legal/accounting services and other support services'

b'Last day at @jaipurlitfest couldn\xe2\x80\x99t get better than this! A great turnout at #BankofBarodaBaithak starting with Yashica Dutt, Sharmila Sen, Urvashi Bautalia and Vivek Tejuja in conversation with feminist campaigner, writer Ruchira Gupta, sharing their experiences and convictions on caste, colour and gender. Followed by a session that interrogated and celebrated the unity in diversity with KR Meera, Shubhangi Swarup and Aruni Kashyap in conversation with Arunava Sinha discussing the literary and lingustic context of their inspiration. Ruben Banerjee, Sonia Singh and Taran Khan in conversation with journalists Faye D\xe2\x80\x99Souza then examined the increasing overlap of fact and fiction in news and media. The post break session began with Rana Ayyub, Max Rodenbeck and Bee Rowlatt in conversation with Mihir Sharma discussing the challenges of reporting protests and civil unrest in a country as divided as contemporary India. Last but not the least, Arvind Krishna Mehrota, Ashok Vajpeyi and Ranjit Hoskote in conversation with award-winning British poet Ruth Padel discussed the contexts of their work as well as the wider canvas of poetics & aesthetics theories at #zeejaipurlitfest2020 The #BankofBaroda stall was flocked all through the day with exciting fun and games.\nIt was great to be a part of one of the biggest literatures festivals of the world.\n#youarewhatyouread'

b'Day4; was a bright Sunday morning with a huge crowd flowing in at @jaipurlitfest . At #BankofBarodaBaithak was a session that bought together a panel of environmental researchers David Wallace-Wells, Marcus Moench and Navroz K Dubash in conversation with Prem Jha. Followed by a full house session with Roshan Ali, Arunava Sinha, Perumal Murugan & Hansda Sowvendra Shekhar in conversation with Manasi Subramaniam, discussing on how they write of masculine identity, territory and challenges they face.\xe2\x80\xac Later Amitabh Kant, Navroz K Dubash and Samir Saran in conversation with journalists Pragya Tiwari, analysed the key pointers and trends in the journey of the world\xe2\x80\x99s largest democracy from an agrarian nation to an urban one. Simon Armitage, one of the world\xe2\x80\x99s greatest living poets, spoke about his life in writing with Nandini Nair. Later in the day was a session by Mita Kapur with Jan Stocklassa and Ravi Subramaniam sharing their views on decoding the phenomenon of the chartbuster. And finally at the end was Anand Gopal, through his dramatic story- No Good Men Among The Living, stunningly layed the workings of America\xe2\x80\x99s longest war and the truth behind its prolonged agony in conversation with author Taran Khan. Through the day, #BankofBaroda stall was packed with visitors enjoying many fun, exciting games and activities at #zeejaipurlitfest2020 \n#youarewhatyouread'

b'Day 3 at @jaipurlitfest began with a long que outside at the #BankofBarodaBaithak for an amazing session of Pragya Tiwari with Yashica Dutt - a New York based journalist & Raghav Chandra discussing the intersections of caste, class, privilege and precarious path to social equity. This was followed by a session with Kavita Puri talking about breaking the silence and confronting the difficult truths about partition with fellow Partition authority Aanchal Malhotra along with Sam Dalrymple.\nPayal Arora & Tarun Khanna talked about the ingenuity of science and technology which fed the artistic imagination and affected innovation. Another insightful session on how reading is important in any form-paperback or e-books was with Nilanjana Roy, Keshav Guha, Chandrahas Choudhury & Navtej Sarna. Introduced by Aanchal Malhotra was Anita Anand describing the remarkable story of one Indian\xe2\x80\x99s 20 year long quest for revenge - those responsible for Jallianwala Bagh massacre. And the day ended with a packed house at Bank of Baroda Baithak, as the author of The Science of Harry Potter, Roger Highfield explored the fascinating links between magic and science with writer and editor Keshav Guha. The #BankofBaroda stall was buzzing with children and people who participated in fun filled activities and games and won amazing gifts! #youarewhatyouread #zeejaipurlitfest2020'

b'Shri Rakesh Sharma, DGM - Head Marketing & Branding, #BankofBaroda talks about the vision of Maharaja Sir Sayajirao Gaekwad III for encouraging art & literature, & how the Bank is continuing the legacy by associating with the @JaipurLitFest. \n#youarewhatyouread #zeejaipurlitfest2020'

b'Day 2 at the @jaipurlitfest started with a full house at #BankofBarodaBaithak to witness Tom Holland in conversation with Swapan Dasgupta, who spoke about Dominion: The Making of the Western Mind. This was followed by an insightful session with environmentalist Pradip Krishen, writers KR Meera and Parvati Sharma discussing on what makes the cut as a piece of literature. The next session explored the Flood and Furry- a book by Viju B along with a discussion on how to reverse the rage of the rivers with the experts Jairam Ramesh, Krupa Ge and Marcus Moench. Later in the day was a session with Anamika in conversation with Nishtha Gautam discussing the book, belief and the core of conviction that sustained the writing practice. Francesc Miralles took the audience through Ikigai - a Japanese Secret to a Long and Happy life along with writer and columnist Nilanjana S Roy. The day ended with Pallavi Raghavan, Samanth Subramanian and Jairam Ramesh talking about research and insights that shape the books followed by a book launch of "A chequered brilliance - The many lives of VK Krishna Menon." Through the day the Bank of Baroda stall witnessed young enthusiasts exploring different activities and enjoying the #zeejaipurlitfest2020 #YouAreWhatYouRead'

b'Day 1 of @jaipurlitfest began by Hon. Chief Minister of Rajasthan Shri Ashok Gehlotji inaugurating the 13th edition of the #zeejaipurlitfest2020. Mr Sanjoy K Roy, MD Teamwork Arts & Festival Co-Directors Ms. Namita Gokhale & Mr. William Dalrymple welcomed the lovers of literature at the festival.\nToday, the sessions at #BankofBarodaBaithak explored the story of a fearless war correspondent while Forrest Gander spoke about his upcoming book Twice Alive - an environmentally focused book of poems. This was followed by Shekhar Pathak - the Himalayan Area researcher sharing his experiences in the mountains. The next session withnessed a meaningful discussion about India\xe2\x80\x99s oldest practises of Yoga and Ayurveda and modern medicine with Hansaji Yogendra, Robert Svoboda, RamKumar & Gautam Sharma on the panel. The day ended with an interesting session on food and culture by Asma Khan & Krishnendu Ray. Through the day, the #BankofBaroda stall was bustling with visitors who participated in fun games. Shri Mahendra Mahanot, GM Jaipur Zone Bank of Baroda presented the winners with prizes. \n#YouAreWhatYouRead'
